Aptos Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">9.0 Building Cons=
ent and Design Requirements<o:p></o:p></span></u></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">The proposed repair w=
ork involves the replacement of existing building products with comparable b=
uilding products in the same position, including
 the repair/replacement of internal timber wall framing and several floor jo=
ists (not a complete or substantial replacement of a wall/floor framing asse=
mbly), the replacement of wall, floor and ceiling linings, and the replaceme=
nt of plumbing fittings and fixtures.
 This is building work that is described in Section 1, Section 12, or Sectio=
n 32 of Schedule 1 of the Building Act 2004 (the Act), thereby satisfying th=
e provisions of Section 42A of the Act as building work that does not requir=
e a building consent. Note that
 although a building consent is not required, the building work being undert=
aken must comply with the building code to the extent required by the Act. I=
n this regard, the provisions of Section 42A (2) of the Act apply for the re=
pair of the existing building,
 in that after the building work is complete, the building must continue to c=
omply with the building code to at least the same extent as it did immediate=
ly before the damage from the event occurred. In effect this means that ther=
e is no requirement to upgrade
 parts of the building that are incidental to or not included in the buildin=
g work.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
