<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">11. The applicable s=
tandard for reinstatement is governed by the express terms of the Policy. It=
 is not determined by trade terminology used
 in a scope of works, nor by subjective expectations as to aesthetic outcome=
. <o:p>
</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">12. Under the Policy=
, Tower=E2=80=99s obligation in the event of an economic repair is to meet t=
he reasonable cost of repairing the house to a standard
 that is reasonably equivalent to its appearance, size, functionality, and r=
elative quality when new, without necessarily reproducing it exactly. That f=
ormulation reflects a well-established distinction in New Zealand insurance l=
aw between a requirement to
 restore functional and qualitative equivalence, and any obligation to deliv=
er a pristine or upgraded outcome.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">13. Where damage is r=
epaired rather than replaced in full, the Policy recognises that the repaire=
d element cannot, in a literal sense, be rendered
 =E2=80=9Cnew=E2=80=9D. In those circumstances, the applicable standard is d=
irected to the materials and workmanship used in the repair, assessed by ref=
erence to whether the completed works restore the relevant element to a cond=
ition that is reasonably equivalent in function
 and quality to its insured state, rather than whether the element is indist=
inguishable from a newly constructed component.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">14. The Policy does n=
ot impose an obligation to improve, upgrade, or replicate owner-driven renov=
ations, nor does it require reinstatement
 to current building standards except to the extent required by law. The use=
 of modern materials and methods is contemplated only as a means of achievin=
g the required functional equivalence, not as a basis for elevating the stan=
dard of the building beyond that
 insured. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">15. The scope prepar=
ed by Asurnz was developed to give effect to this contractual standard. It r=
eflects the assessor=E2=80=99s determination of what
 work is reasonably required to repair the insured damage, including replace=
ment where necessary and cleaning, repainting, or reinstatement where replac=
ement is not required. The absence of the phrase =E2=80=9Cwhen new=E2=80=9D i=
n the scope does not alter the standard to be
 applied, which is fixed by the Policy wording itself. <o:p></o:p></span></p=
>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">16. Any assessment o=
f the adequacy of the scope or of completed works must therefore be undertak=
en by reference to the Policy definition of
 repair cost, and not by reference to a requirement to return repaired eleme=
nts to their precise pre-loss condition or to an elevated aesthetic standard=
 achieved through prior renovations.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US">17. Where Tower elec=
ts to manage the repairs, the works will be carried out with reasonable care=
 and skill and in compliance with applicable
 legal requirements. That obligation does not require the highest possible f=
inish or the adoption of a particular trade standard unless expressly requir=
ed by the Policy or otherwise agreed.
<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:11.0pt;font-family:&quot;Apt=
os Display&quot;,sans-serif;mso-fareast-language:EN-US"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></s=
